    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
      <p>Thyroid cancer presents a paradox that reveals, with uncommon clarity, how medicine can go wrong in two opposite directions simultaneously.</p>

      <p>For the past three decades, thyroid cancer was on a trajectory that looked epidemiologically alarming. Incidence rates tripled in the United States between 1975 and 2015. Other countries with advanced imaging infrastructure showed similar or steeper curves. The natural interpretation — that something was causing more thyroid cancer — drove funding, raised anxiety, and produced a clinical response calibrated to a genuine epidemic.</p>

      <p>The incidence curve was real. The epidemic, mostly, was not.</p>

      <p>A series of analyses beginning around 2014 established what retrospective examination of the data had suggested for years: the vast majority of the rising thyroid cancer incidence was driven by the increasing use of neck ultrasound and CT imaging, which detected small papillary microcarcinomas — tumors under 10 mm — that had always existed in the population but had never been found because nobody had looked for them. Studies of autopsy series found occult papillary thyroid microcarcinomas in anywhere from 5% to 36% of individuals who died of unrelated causes, with the higher estimates from populations where thyroid tissue was systematically sectioned. These were clinically invisible cancers that had coexisted with their hosts, causing no harm and never destined to.</p>

      <p>The machine of modern oncology found them, labeled them cancer, and treated them with surgery, radioactive iodine, lifelong monitoring, and the psychological weight of a cancer diagnosis. In doing so, it almost certainly caused net harm to a large fraction of the patients it diagnosed.</p>

      <p>This is the overdiagnosis problem in thyroid cancer — still not fully resolved, still generating excess surgery in many clinical settings, and now partially addressed by a set of 2025 guidelines that represent the most significant recalibration of thyroid cancer management in a decade. But the overdiagnosis story should not obscure the other half of the picture: the advanced thyroid cancers that are genuinely dangerous, that were undertreated before targeted molecular therapies, and that are now being addressed with a precision that was simply unavailable twenty years ago.</p>

      <p>Both stories need telling.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="the-spectrum" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Spectrum: What Thyroid Cancer Actually Is</h2>

      <p>Thyroid cancer is not one disease. It is a family of diseases with radically different natural histories, molecular drivers, and prognoses. Understanding where the overdiagnosis problem lives requires understanding this spectrum.</p>

      <p><strong>Papillary thyroid carcinoma (PTC)</strong> accounts for roughly 80–85% of all thyroid cancers. It is the most common endocrine malignancy. Most papillary thyroid cancers — particularly the microcarcinomas under 1 cm — are indolent: they grow slowly or not at all, rarely metastasize, and have a long-term survival rate of approximately 99% with appropriate treatment. Multifocal PTC, where multiple small foci are present, is common and does not consistently predict more aggressive behavior.</p>

      <p><strong>Follicular thyroid carcinoma (FTC)</strong> accounts for approximately 10–15% of cases. It is more likely to spread hematogenously — through blood — to distant sites including lung and bone, rather than via lymph nodes. Its prognosis is generally good but somewhat less favorable than PTC.</p>

      <p><strong>Poorly differentiated thyroid carcinoma (PDTC)</strong> and <strong>anaplastic thyroid carcinoma (ATC)</strong> together account for a small fraction of cases but carry dramatically different prognoses. PDTC has an intermediate aggressiveness. ATC is one of the most lethal malignancies in oncology: it is largely unresponsive to radioactive iodine, has a median survival measured in months, and has historically been managed palliatively. New molecular targeted therapies, particularly for BRAF-mutated anaplastic cancers, are beginning to change this, but slowly.</p>

      <p><strong>Medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC)</strong> arises from parafollicular C-cells rather than follicular cells, does not take up iodine, and in 25% of cases is associated with germline mutations in the RET proto-oncogene. Familial MTC allows for prophylactic thyroidectomy in RET mutation carriers — one of the most successful preventive surgical interventions in oncology.</p>

      <p>The overdiagnosis problem is almost entirely confined to the low end of the papillary spectrum: microcarcinomas that would never cause symptoms or death. The genuine clinical danger lies at the other end — in poorly differentiated and anaplastic cancers, in RAI-refractory differentiated cancers, and in metastatic disease.</p>
    </section>

