    <section id="2025-ata-guidelines" class="reveal">
      <h2>The 2025 ATA Guidelines: A New Surgical Calculus</h2>

      <p>The 2025 American Thyroid Association Management Guidelines for Adult Patients with Differentiated Thyroid Cancer — downloaded over 200,000 times in the months following their August publication — represent the most significant formal recalibration of thyroid cancer management since the 2015 guidelines.</p>

      <p>The central revision is in the extent of initial surgery. For years, the default for most thyroid cancer diagnoses — including small, low-risk papillary cancers — was total thyroidectomy: removal of the entire gland. The logic was to facilitate radioactive iodine ablation of any remaining tissue and to use thyroglobulin as a reliable surveillance marker. The consequences were lifelong thyroid hormone replacement, permanent hypoparathyroidism in a significant minority of patients (parathyroid glands are frequently damaged or inadvertently removed during total thyroidectomy), and vocal cord paralysis from recurrent laryngeal nerve damage.</p>

      <p>The new guidelines formally incorporate a decade of evidence showing that for low-risk, small PTC, thyroid lobectomy — removal of only the affected lobe — achieves outcomes equivalent to total thyroidectomy in terms of disease-specific survival and recurrence rates. The recurrence rates after lobectomy for low-risk PTC are low enough, and the life-years lost from lobectomy patients dying of thyroid cancer are rare enough, that the morbidity of total thyroidectomy cannot be justified on benefit grounds.</p>

      <p>The 2025 guidelines also expand risk stratification considerably, moving toward a more individualized framework that accounts for tumor size, nodal status, extrathyroidal extension, molecular markers, and patient factors. The goal is to identify specifically which patients benefit from additional treatment — including radioactive iodine — rather than applying a uniform escalation to everyone whose diagnosis exceeds a threshold.</p>
    </section>

