    <section id="active-surveillance" class="reveal">
      <h2>Active Surveillance: Learning to Wait</h2>

      <p>The most philosophically challenging shift in thyroid cancer management is active surveillance for papillary microcarcinomas — the direct clinical response to the overdiagnosis recognition.</p>

      <p>The foundational data come from Japan. Researchers at Kuma Hospital and the Cancer Institute Hospital in Tokyo began prospective active surveillance protocols for papillary microcarcinomas in the 1990s and have published long-term outcome data showing that the vast majority of these small cancers do not grow or metastasize over 5–10 years of observation. The growth rate is approximately 5–10% of lesions enlarging by more than 3 mm over 10 years. The risk of lymph node metastasis in observed patients who never receive surgery is low and, when it occurs, remains easily treatable.</p>

      <p>Active surveillance is not universal. Exclusion criteria include tumors adjacent to the recurrent laryngeal nerve or trachea, cases with suspicious lymph nodes at presentation, aggressive cytological features, and patient-specific factors including significant anxiety, poor follow-up compliance, and pregnancy (where active surveillance creates monitoring complications). But for appropriately selected patients — a low-risk tumor in a patient who understands the surveillance requirements — active surveillance avoids surgery, its complications, and the lifelong pharmacological management of post-thyroidectomy hypothyroidism.</p>

      <p>The North American evidence base for active surveillance has been slower to accumulate than the Japanese data, partly because the medicolegal culture in the United States creates institutional reluctance to recommend observation for anything labeled "cancer." Multiple North American centers have now published their active surveillance cohort data, and the outcomes are consistent with the Japanese experience. The 2025 ATA guidelines explicitly include active surveillance as an option for low-risk microcarcinomas.</p>

      <p>The cultural barrier remains real. Telling a patient they have cancer and then recommending they do nothing requires a calibration of risk communication that most clinicians were not trained for. The word "cancer" triggers a categorical imperative in most people. Reframing small papillary thyroid lesions as "low-risk thyroid neoplasms of follicular origin" — a nomenclature change the WHO has actually adopted for the lowest-risk encapsulated non-invasive follicular variant PTC — is one approach to managing this problem. It resets the psychological stakes while accurately representing the biology.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="thermal-ablation" class="reveal">
      <h2>Thermal Ablation: Burning Without Cutting</h2>

      <p>For papillary microcarcinomas where the patient prefers intervention over surveillance but wants to avoid surgery, radiofrequency ablation (RFA) and microwave ablation (MWA) have matured into clinically validated alternatives.</p>

      <p>These techniques use image-guided needle electrodes to thermally destroy tumor tissue in situ, with real-time ultrasound monitoring. They are performed under local anesthesia as outpatient procedures. They do not require general anesthesia. They preserve the thyroid gland and the contralateral lobe. They avoid the risks of open neck surgery — parathyroid damage, recurrent laryngeal nerve injury, infection, and scarring.</p>

      <p>A 10-center study published in <em>Radiology</em> in 2024, comparing microwave ablation to surgical resection for multifocal T1N0M0 papillary thyroid carcinoma, found the non-surgical approach was competitive on oncological outcomes while delivering substantially lower morbidity. A systematic review and meta-analysis in <em>JAMA Otolaryngology</em> in 2022, examining radiofrequency ablation for papillary microcarcinomas, found very low rates of incomplete ablation and local recurrence, with high rates of primary treatment success.</p>

      <p>The management of thyroid nodules has evolved from a paradigm in which the options were either surgery or observation, to one defined by precision imaging, cytology, and molecular diagnostics, with minimally invasive options now available. This sentence from the 2025 AACE Year in Review is accurate, but it understates the speed of the transition. Five years ago, RFA for thyroid cancer outside of clinical trials was unusual in the United States. Today, it is a guideline-acknowledged option. The trajectory is toward it becoming standard of care for carefully selected patients, particularly as the technology improves and more clinicians acquire the technique.</p>
    </section>

