    <section id="molecular-revolution" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Molecular Revolution in Thyroid Cancer</h2>

      <p>The biological drivers of thyroid malignancy are now characterized at sufficient molecular resolution to stratify risk, guide adjuvant therapy decisions, and — for advanced disease — select targeted treatments.</p>

      <p>The major molecular drivers divide roughly by clinical behavior:</p>

      <p><strong>BRAF V600E mutation</strong> is present in approximately 45–60% of papillary thyroid cancers. BRAF V600E activates the MAPK/ERK signaling pathway constitutively, driving unregulated cell proliferation. In differentiated PTC, BRAF mutation correlates with slightly more aggressive behavior, reduced radioiodine uptake, and higher risk of recurrence. In anaplastic thyroid carcinoma, BRAF V600E is the most important actionable target: the combination of dabrafenib (a BRAF inhibitor) and trametinib (a MEK inhibitor) has produced response rates and overall survival improvements in BRAF-mutated ATC that were unimaginable with prior regimens.</p>

      <p><strong>RET/PTC rearrangements</strong> drive a significant minority of papillary thyroid cancers, particularly in post-radiation populations (the Chernobyl cohort, for example, shows dramatically elevated rates of RET/PTC rearrangement-driven PTC). RET inhibitors — selpercatinib and pralsetinib — are now FDA-approved for RET fusion-driven thyroid cancers and medullary thyroid carcinoma, with response rates in the 60–70% range in heavily pre-treated patients.</p>

      <p><strong>RAS mutations</strong> (HRAS, KRAS, NRAS) are the predominant drivers of follicular thyroid cancer and are found in a subset of papillary cancers and poorly differentiated tumors. They tend to correlate with follicular growth pattern and do not respond to BRAF-targeting agents.</p>

      <p><strong>TERT promoter mutations</strong> are found in approximately 7–25% of differentiated thyroid cancers, with increasing frequency in dedifferentiated tumors. Their presence correlates strongly with more aggressive behavior, higher recurrence rates, and worse survival — and they appear to act synergistically with BRAF V600E. The combination of BRAF V600E and TERT promoter mutation identifies a subset of differentiated thyroid cancers with substantially worse prognosis than BRAF or TERT mutation alone.</p>

      <p><strong>ALK fusions, NTRK fusions, and other kinase-activating alterations</strong> occur in smaller subsets and are increasingly targetable with approved agents — larotrectinib and entrectinib for NTRK fusions, lorlatinib and crizotinib for ALK fusions.</p>

      <p>The clinical implication of this molecular landscape is a shift away from histological staging as the primary risk-stratification tool toward molecular profiling. A 3 cm papillary thyroid cancer with no BRAF or TERT mutation and no lymph node involvement has a fundamentally different risk profile than a 1.5 cm papillary cancer with both BRAF V600E and a TERT promoter mutation. The 2025 ATA guidelines incorporate this, building molecular data explicitly into risk stratification.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="molecular-diagnostics" class="reveal">
      <h2>Molecular Diagnostics: The Indeterminate Nodule Problem</h2>

      <p>Approximately 20–25% of fine-needle aspiration (FNA) biopsies of thyroid nodules return cytologically indeterminate results — the Bethesda III and IV categories, which correspond to "atypia of undetermined significance" and "follicular neoplasm." Historically, these results led to diagnostic lobectomy in most cases, because cytology alone could not distinguish between benign follicular adenoma and follicular thyroid carcinoma.</p>

      <p>Gene expression classifiers — molecular tests performed on biopsy material — have significantly improved the management of indeterminate nodules. The Afirma Gene Sequencing Classifier, Thyroseq v3, and ThyGeNEXT/ThyraMIR are now widely used to triage Bethesda III and IV nodules toward either surgery or observation, depending on the molecular signature.</p>

      <p>The Afirma classifier, for example, reports results as "benign" or "suspicious." Afirma-benign results have a negative predictive value for malignancy of approximately 95% in appropriately selected populations — sufficient to defer surgery for the majority of indeterminate nodules. Thyroseq v3 provides information not only on malignancy risk but on specific molecular drivers, which informs surgical planning.</p>

      <p>These tests are not perfect. False negatives occur. The test characteristics vary by institutional case mix and baseline malignancy prevalence in the population being tested. But the reduction in diagnostic lobectomies for ultimately benign nodules — with all of the associated morbidity and post-surgical hypothyroidism — represents a meaningful improvement in patient outcomes.</p>

      <p>The 2025 Swiss Empa technology that creates three-dimensional AI imaging of thyroid biopsy specimens without destroying the sample adds another dimension: non-destructive assessment that preserves tissue for downstream molecular testing if the initial analysis is insufficient. The integration of AI with molecular diagnostics is still emerging, but the trajectory is toward a diagnostic pipeline that combines imaging, molecular, and cytological information in ways that reduce both false positives (unnecessary surgery) and false negatives (missed cancers).</p>
    </section>

    <section id="radioactive-iodine" class="reveal">
      <h2>Radioactive Iodine: The Recalibration</h2>

      <p>Radioactive iodine (RAI) ablation — ingesting radioactive I-131, which the thyroid accumulates specifically due to the sodium-iodide symporter, destroying remaining thyroid tissue and micrometastases — has been a cornerstone of differentiated thyroid cancer treatment for decades. The 2025 ATA guidelines signal a significant recalibration of its use.</p>

      <p>The core change: RAI is now formally discouraged for low-risk differentiated thyroid cancer after lobectomy or even total thyroidectomy, absent high-risk features. The evidence accumulated over the past decade shows that RAI ablation does not improve disease-specific survival or recurrence rates in low-risk patients, while carrying real morbidity — salivary gland dysfunction, dry eye, radiation-associated secondary malignancies, and reproductive effects in younger patients.</p>

      <p>For intermediate and high-risk patients, RAI remains an important and effective tool. But the reflexive post-thyroidectomy RAI that characterized thyroid cancer management through much of the 2000s and 2010s is now formally, guidelines-explicitly, inappropriate for the majority of differentiated thyroid cancer patients.</p>
    </section>

