    <section id="the-anaplastic-exception" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Anaplastic Exception</h2>

      <p>Anaplastic thyroid carcinoma deserves special attention because the recent therapeutic advances are genuinely dramatic and because the disease itself is so catastrophically severe that any improvement is noteworthy.</p>

      <p>ATC is rare — approximately 1–2% of all thyroid cancers — but accounts for approximately 40% of thyroid cancer deaths despite its rarity. The median survival from diagnosis was historically 3–6 months. Five-year survival rates were in the low single digits.</p>

      <p>For patients whose ATC harbors BRAF V600E mutations — approximately 40–50% of cases — the combination of dabrafenib and trametinib (marketed as Tafinlar + Mekinist) has produced responses that were previously unheard of: partial or complete responses in 50–60% of BRAF-mutated ATC patients, with median overall survival extending to 18+ months in some series. These are not cures — ATC remains lethal in most cases — but they represent the first meaningful pharmacological improvement in a cancer that had been essentially untreatable. The lesson is what molecular targeting of the right driver can accomplish, and it is already changing the diagnostic workflow for ATC to ensure BRAF testing occurs immediately at diagnosis to identify who can benefit.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="what-the-next-ten-years-look-like" class="reveal">
      <h2>What the Next Ten Years Look Like</h2>

      <p>The thyroid cancer trajectory for the next decade involves several converging technologies: more precise molecular profiling at diagnosis; AI-augmented ultrasound and biopsy pathology; broader access to minimally invasive thermal ablation for selected patients; and, for advanced disease, the continuation of the targeted therapy revolution that has already produced results in BRAF-, RET-, and NTRK-driven cancers.</p>

      <p>Universal application of active surveillance for low-risk microcarcinomas, if adopted broadly, would dramatically reduce the net harm currently produced by the overdiagnosis pipeline. Whether the legal environment, the clinical culture, and the patient expectation that "cancer" requires "treatment" will allow this depends on factors outside the laboratory.</p>

      <p>The paradox with which this section opened — a disease simultaneously over-treated at its least dangerous end and under-treated at its most dangerous end — is being resolved, slowly, from both directions. The evidence base has done its job. Whether the practice catches up is the perennial question.</p>
    </section>

